This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category cs.CL (Computation and Language) because it deals with techniques for minimizing weighted tree automata, which are a powerful formalism for modeling natural language syntax and semantics. Additionally, the paper evaluates the proposed method on real-world data originating in newswire treebank, which further supports its relevance to the field of computational linguistics. 

The paper may also be relevant to the arXiv CS sub-category cs.LG (Machine Learning) because it proposes a method for minimizing probabilistic models, which is a common task in machine learning. 

The paper's focus on the singular value decomposition (SVD) of the underlying Hankel matrix suggests that it may be relevant to the arXiv CS sub-category cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), which deals with efficient algorithms for manipulating and analyzing large datasets. 

The paper's use of latent-variable PCFGs suggests that it may be relevant to the arXiv CS sub-category cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence), which deals with techniques for modeling and reasoning about complex systems. 

Finally, the paper's focus on approximation error and stability suggests that it may be relevant to the arXiv CS sub-category cs.SI (Social and Information Networks), which deals with the analysis and optimization of complex systems with many interacting components.
